6_11	0.11874079	For those who are truly concerned about pesticides in conventional food, the safest alternative is organic food.
6_12	0.053325611	On another issue, a reader wondered about the nutritional value of vegetables in soup, explaining that her husband called soup ``dead vegetables'' because they are cooked so long.
6_13	0.087063318	Water-soluble vitamins B and C do leach out of vegetables when they are cooked in liquid, but in this case they go directly into the soup.
6_14	0.09235629	To keep the vegetables from looking dead, add the most tender ones just long enough to cook and contribute some flavor without turning to mush.
6_15	0.094020539	Still another reader wanted to know how pineapple juice and carrot juice can still have fiber in them after they have been processed.
6_16	0.082129328	The best source of that kind of information is Harold McGee, the author of ``On Food and Cooking'' (Scribner, 1984).
6_17	0.091560015	As he explains, there are two kinds of fiber, soluble and insoluble.
6_18	0.099291966	Pectin, which is used to gel jellies, is soluble fiber.
6_19	0.088992695	It doesn't appear to have any texture, but it does, so you might not be able to tell it was in the juice.
6_20	0.093341209	Cellulose and lignin are insoluble fibers.
6_21	0.090751195	The fiber in a glass of pineapple or carrot juice is soluble, and it cannot be seen because it is suspended in the liquid.
6_22	0.094682514	Insoluble fiber, if it is there, is the sediment, what eventually falls to the bottom of the glass.
6_23	0.086950842	Another reader had a more pressing question: Can you make a low-fat blue cheese dressing like the bottled kind at home?
6_24	0.099747118	Yes and no.
6_25	0.091080225	You can make a low-fat blue cheese dressing, but not like the one in the bottle.
6_26	0.092631914	In my version, which is given below, there is no guar gum, used as a thickener.
6_27	0.096857605	Because blue cheese has such a strong flavor, not much is needed, and that keeps the calories and fat down.
6_28	0.091759616	This dressing is delicious on ripe tomatoes or Belgian endive and as an alternative to the usual dressing for coleslaw or potato salad.
6_29	0.080573193	To make enough for four people, mash two ounces (four tablespoons) of blue cheese with six tablespoons of plain nonfat yogurt, two tablespoons of brandy and a couple of pinches of cayenne.
6_30	0.1032303	Mix well.
6_31	0.091133123	The dressing will keep for a week or two in the refrigerator, tightly covered.
